    • Class triana.types.GraphType extends TrianaType implements Serializable

      • Serialized Fields

        • independentVariables

          int independentVariables
          Parameter independentVariables is an int that defines the number of independent variables that describe the object. This is essentially the dimension of the graph of the object. Thus, a sphere in three dimensions has independentVariables = 2, since the postion of any point on the sphere is a function of only two variables, e.g. the latitude and longitude. When the object is drawn, these variables may or may not correspond to independent dimensions in the space in which the object is portrayed.

          The Hashtable dataContainer contains dependentVariables arrays, each of which has independentVariables dimensions, which contain the data that describe the dependent variables; and independentVariables 1-D arrays of doubles or Triplets that describe the spacing of the values of the independent variables at which the data are represented. The independent variables must be given by doubles. The dependent variable arrays can have any Object component type.

          As a special case, it is allowed to have independentVariables = 0. This represents a constant: the dependent variables are arrays consisting of only one element each. The type of the elements are still arbitrary.

          It is initialised to -1 as a signal for an empty data set.

          See Also:
          Triplet

        • dependentVariables

          int dependentVariables
          Parameter dependentVariables is an int that defines the number of dependent variables represented in the data set. These could, for example, be the three coordinates (x,y,z) of a point on the surface of a sphere being drawn in 3 dimensions. They are functions of the independent variables, such as the latitude and longitude. There must be dependentVariables such arrays, each with independentVariables dimensions, and their components can be any Objects: doubles, arrays, colours, etc. Of course, only objects that a graphing unit can understand will be graphed.

          It is initialised to -1 as a signal for an empty data set.

        • triplet

          boolean[] triplet
          Parameter array triplet is a boolean[] that carries information about whether the data associated with a particular independent variable are represented by a Triplet, which is an object that contains three numbers from which one can generate a uniformly spaced one-dimensional data set: length, start, and step. The value true indicates that the data Object is a Triplet; false that it is not, ie that it is either a full one-dimensional array. If the data are complex, then they cannot be represented by a Triplet.

          The array triplet must be dimensioned to have at least independentVariables elements in the data object constructors.

          See Also:
          Triplet

        • independentComplex

          boolean[] independentComplex
          Parameter array independentComplex is a boolean[] that carries information about whether the data associated with a particular independent variable are real or complex. Complex data are represented by two real arrays of identical structure. The array independentComplex must be dimensioned to have at least independentVariables elements in the data object constructors.

          Parameter array dependentComplex similarly carries information about whether the data associated with a particular dependent variable are real or complex. This only makes sense if the data component type is a numerical one; otherwise this must be false. The array dependentComplex must be dimensioned to have at least dependentVariables elements in the data object constructors.

        • dependentComplex

          boolean[] dependentComplex

        • dimensionLengths

          int[] dimensionLengths
          Parameter array dimensionLengths is an int[] that contains the length of the dimension of each independent variable (i.e. the number of data elements in that direction) in the data array. The number of elements in dimensionLengths is independentVariables.

        • dependentVariableDimensions

          java.util.ArrayList<E> dependentVariableDimensions
          Parameter array dependentVariableDimensions is an ArrayList that contains int[]'s that give the lengths of the dimension of each independent variable (i.e. the number of data elements in that direction) in the data array. The number of elements in dependentVariableDimensions is dependentVariables. The length of the int[] in each element is independentVariables.

        • dataArrayTypeNames

          java.lang.String[] dataArrayTypeNames
          Parameter array dataArrayTypeNames is an array of Strings that give the type names of each of the dependent variable arrays. This array must be dimensioned to have at least dependentVariables dimensions in data object constructors.

        • title

          java.lang.String title
          Parameter title is a String that contains the title that should be displayed by a graph of the data.

        • labels

          java.util.Hashtable<K,V> labels
          Parameter labels is a Hashtable containing text labels that describe the data held in dataContainer. They should be short enough to be used for the axes of a graph. The keys to the Hashtable are the Strings in the String arrays independentNames and dependentNames, which also key the data arrays in dataContainer. However, since the real and imaginary parts of the data should have the same basic name, there are only independentVariables + dependentVariables labels, and they are keyed by the Strings for the real parts of the respective data variables (i.e. even-numbered elements of independentNames and dependentNames). Graphing/display methods that present complex data should append appropriate modifiers to the basic label, such as "(real)", "(imag)", "(magnitude)", or "(phase)".

        • independentNames

          java.lang.String[] independentNames
          Parameters independentNames and dependentNames are String[] arrays consisting of Strings that will be used as keys into the Hashtables dataContainer and labels. The keys are Strings of the form "IV 0 real", "IV 0 imag", "IV 1 real", ..., "DV 0 real", etc, where "IV" denotes the independent variables and "DV" the dependent variables. There are 2 * independentVariables + 2 * dependentVariables elements in this array. In this way the methods that access this data can access it as if it were an array with components 0, 1, 2, .., 2 * independentVariables + 2 * dependentVariables - 1, rather than a Hashtable. They use the indices to get access the keys that are held in these arrays and then the access methods use these keys into the Hashtable. This allows uniform data access even when the number of data sets is not known ahead of time, which will be the case here, even though the number of dimensions is fixed in any data object, since data are allowed to be real or complex. If the data were stored directly in a Vector or other list, then the position of, say, the real part of the data for the 3rd axis would depend on whether the data for the first and second axes were real or imaginary. This would complicate bookkeeping. By storing keys in these arrays, which contain a key for each possible data set, and then using the keys in a Hashtable, the position of the actual data set in the Hashtable is not needed.

          java.lang.String[] dependentNames
